<article>
    <h1>3 Aug&#xAD;mented re&#xAD;al&#xAD;ity</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210103/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-03"><time>2021-01-03</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline">Chan&#xAD;tal Sa&#xAD;jan&#xD;&#xA;Se&#xAD;nior Correspond&#xAD;ent</span>
    </section>

    <p>Aug­mented re­al­ity (AR) is ex­pected to grow ex­po­nen­tially this year in Sin­ga­pore with the roll­out of 5G in­fra­struc­ture from this month till 2025, in­creas­ing the band­width for In­ter­net of Things (IoT) de­vices.</p>
    <p>Un­like vir­tual re­al­ity (VR) which trans­ports users into an al­ter­nate uni­verse and blocks out the real world, AR melds both to­gether.</p>
    <p>It lay­ers in­for­ma­tion from the In­ter­net, en­abling Star Wars-style holo­grams to ap­pear in real time and space.</p>
    <p>The tech­nol­ogy is also ex­pected to trans­form the global mar­ket­place by pro­vid­ing more re­al­is­tic and en­ter­tain­ing dig­i­tal ex­pe­ri­ences that will ben­e­fit in­dus­tries such as de­sign, re­tail, hos­pi­tal­ity, ed­u­ca­tion and health.</p>
    <p>Sin­ga­pore’s 5G li­cences were awarded last year to Sing­tel and a joint ven­ture be­tween StarHub and M1. Two stand­alone net­works are in the works to cover at least half the coun­try by the end of next year and the whole is­land by end-2025.</p>
    <p>Last year, Mr Marco Bardelli, ex­ec­u­tive di­rec­tor of Sin­ga­pore­based in­te­grated me­dia en­ter­tain­ment and cre­ative ser­vices com­pany In­fi­nite Stu­dios, pre­dicted that AR head­gear will soon lose its bulky shape and be­come fi­nessed into eye­wear.</p>
    <p>“The holy grail is when AR head­gear can be de­signed to look like Ray-Bans,” he told The Straits Times in June.</p>
    <p>Barely three months l ater i n Septem­ber, Face­book chief ex­ec­u­tive Mark Zucker­berg an­nounced it would launch its own tech ver­sion of Ray-Ban glasses in a joint ven­ture with Franco-Ital­ian eye­wear gi­ant Es­silorLux­ot­tica.</p>
    <p>A Face­book post read: “Imag­ine a pair of glasses that add a 3D layer of use­ful, con­tex­tu­ally rel­e­vant and mean­ing­ful in­for­ma­tion on top of the phys­i­cal world.</p>
    <p>“Such a de­vice could help us per­form ev­ery­day tasks bet­ter – like find­ing your keys, nav­i­gat­ing a new city or cap­tur­ing a mo­ment.”</p>
    <p>The part­ner­ship is seen by in­dus­try watch­ers as a brave, new foray into the lu­cra­tive wear­able tech mar­ket, which will blend Face­book apps and tech­nolo­gies with Lux­ot­tica brands and Es­silor lens tech­nol­ogy.</p>
    <p>How­ever, Mr Bardelli, who is also the se­nior ex­ec­u­tive di­rec­tor of the Nongsa Dig­i­tal Park i n Batam, ob­serves not much has tran­spired since the Face­book an­nounce­ment three months ago, al­though he notes “Mr Zucker­berg high­lighted once again Face­book’s firm com­mit­ment to AR at the com­pany’s year-end ex­ec­u­tive meet­ing”.</p>
    <p>The lack of news, says Mr Bardelli, could just be a re­flec­tion of how guarded com­pa­nies are to­day about the release of new, in­no­va­tive and dis­rup­tive AR hard­ware.</p>
    <p>“Noth­ing leaks out, all is very much top se­cret, bil­lions of dol­lars are spent in R&D. This is in­deed se­ri­ous busi­ness,” he adds.</p>
    <p>Mean­while, he says the key to un­lock­ing the po­ten­tial of AR is 5G, which is al­ready be­ing rolled out here and else­where.</p>
    <p>“Dif­fer­ent from VR, the AR ex­pe­ri­ence is all about plac­ing dig­i­tal im­ages or holo­grams within the con­text of the re­al­ity that sur­rounds the in­di­vid­ual util­is­ing AR-en­abled hard­ware.</p>
    <p>“For a truly im­mer­sive and en­joy­able ex­pe­ri­ence, the plac­ing of such dig­i­tal ob­jects in front of your eyes needs to be pre­cise and strictly cor­re­lated to where you are and what you are look­ing at. Only 5G can en­able this un­prece­dented pre­ci­sion,” says Mr Bardelli.</p>
    <p>In­fi­nite Stu­dios has also re­acted to the 5G roll-out in Sin­ga­pore by set­ting up a ded­i­cated divi­sion with a fo­cus on de­vel­op­ing ap­pli­ca­tions geared to­wards AR.</p>
    <p>“Be­sides projects that will ben­e­fit from the mix of 5G and AR, we are also de­vel­op­ing a rev­o­lu­tion­ary ap­pli­ca­tion that could pro­vide an im­mense i mpact on Sin­ga­pore tourism, another eco­nomic sec­tor badly hit by the pan­demic.</p>
    <p>“I know you would like to know more, but this is top se­cret too,” he adds with a wink. “Just like those AR Ray-Bans.”</p>
    <p>For a truly im­mer­sive and en­joy­able ex­pe­ri­ence, the plac­ing of such dig­i­tal ob­jects in front of your eyes needs to be pre­cise and strictly cor­re­lated to where you are and what you are look­ing at. Only 5G can en­able this un­prece­dented pre­ci­sion.</p>
    <p>MR MARCO BARDELLI, ex­ec­u­tive di­rec­tor of in­te­grated me­dia en­ter­tain­ment and cre­ative ser­vices com­pany In­fi­nite Stu­dios, on 5G be­ing the key to un­lock­ing the po­ten­tial of AR. Sin­ga­pore’s 5G in­fra­struc­ture roll-out be­gins this year</p>

